1
00:00:00,640 --> 00:00:02,399
The cozy English.

2
00:00:02,399 --> 00:00:04,160
Learn English slowly.

3
00:00:04,160 --> 00:00:04,659
Hello.

4
00:00:06,299 --> 00:00:07,699
Hello, everyone.

5
00:00:07,900 --> 00:00:11,859
Welcome back to another episode of the cozy English.

6
00:00:12,415 --> 00:00:17,655
I'm Emma, and I am feeling absolutely fantastic today.

7
00:00:17,854 --> 00:00:19,735
I've got my favorite tea.

8
00:00:19,935 --> 00:00:25,335
The sun is shining through the window, and I feel like I'm vibrating with energy.

9
00:00:26,150 --> 00:00:34,350
Daniel, you, on the other hand, you look like you've been through a car wash without the car.

10
00:00:34,949 --> 00:00:36,830
Hi, Emma.

11
00:00:37,030 --> 00:00:38,110
Hello, everyone.

12
00:00:39,934 --> 00:00:40,775
Yeah.

13
00:00:40,735 --> 00:00:43,655
Car wash is a generous way to put it.

14
00:00:44,095 --> 00:00:47,655
I'm feeling the exact opposite of you today.

15
00:00:48,254 --> 00:00:50,215
I feel heavy.

16
00:00:51,150 --> 00:00:54,470
My brain feels like it's made of wet cement,

17
00:00:54,670 --> 00:01:02,229
and I've been sitting here for twenty minutes just trying to remember why I even liked the idea of being an adult.

18
00:01:02,269 --> 00:01:03,110
Oh, no.

19
00:01:03,755 --> 00:01:07,634
Is it just one of those mornings where everything goes wrong?

20
00:01:08,155 --> 00:01:10,755
It's been one of those weeks.

21
00:01:11,355 --> 00:01:18,515
My laptop charger frayed, my neighbor decided to start a heavy metal band at 2AM,

22
00:01:19,030 --> 00:01:22,509
and I spilled coffee on my favorite book.

23
00:01:23,110 --> 00:01:30,509
I found myself sitting on the floor earlier thinking, why is life so hard sometimes?

24
00:01:30,870 --> 00:01:33,869
Why can't things just work?

25
00:01:35,445 --> 00:01:42,605
I feel like I'm trying my best, but the universe is just saying no.

26
00:01:42,965 --> 00:01:46,905
Well, first of all, I'm sorry about the coffee.

27
00:01:46,905 --> 00:01:48,765
That's a genuine tragedy.

28
00:01:49,339 --> 00:01:55,940
But I actually think your heavy mood is the perfect starting point for today's topic.

29
00:01:56,460 --> 00:01:59,439
We're going to dive into why we feel this way

30
00:01:59,439 --> 00:02:03,460
and how to navigate those days when the world feels like a mountain.

31
00:02:04,055 --> 00:02:10,095
For our listeners who are struggling to catch every word of Daniel's existential crisis,

32
00:02:10,295 --> 00:02:14,175
remember that the full PDF script is in the description.

33
00:02:14,615 --> 00:02:17,775
It's got all the vocabulary and idioms we're using,

34
00:02:18,180 --> 00:02:23,739
which is a great way to study even when you're feeling as low as Daniel is.

35
00:02:24,260 --> 00:02:26,700
Definitely get that PDF.

36
00:02:27,219 --> 00:02:32,619
My vocabulary gets a bit dark when I'm tired, so you'll want the notes.

37
00:02:33,624 --> 00:02:38,785
But, Emma, seriously, you're always so up.

38
00:02:39,225 --> 00:02:44,544
Do you actually have a secret, or are you just better at pretending?

39
00:02:45,540 --> 00:02:48,200
Because when I see people like you

40
00:02:48,200 --> 00:02:50,920
or people on my social media feed

41
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:53,720
who seem to have these aesthetic,

42
00:02:53,720 --> 00:02:59,660
frictionless lives, it makes my own struggle feel like a personal failure.

43
00:03:00,795 --> 00:03:08,195
I start thinking that if life is this hard, I must be doing something fundamentally wrong.

44
00:03:08,475 --> 00:03:11,155
That's the expectation gap, Daniel.

45
00:03:11,595 --> 00:03:14,755
We live in a world of instant gratification.

46
00:03:15,190 --> 00:03:17,550
We order food in one click.

47
00:03:17,590 --> 00:03:19,630
We watch movies instantly.

48
00:03:19,670 --> 00:03:23,230
We get five second answers to complex questions.

49
00:03:23,830 --> 00:03:28,510
Our brains have been trained to expect that life should be frictionless.

50
00:03:29,315 --> 00:03:35,755
When actual friction happens, like your charger breaking, it feels like a system failure.

51
00:03:36,195 --> 00:03:39,115
You aren't just dealing with a broken charger.

52
00:03:39,235 --> 00:03:44,795
You're dealing with the shame of having a problem while the rest of the world looks perfect.

53
00:03:45,609 --> 00:03:51,010
So you're saying the problem is my head, not the charger.

54
00:03:51,690 --> 00:03:56,450
That feels a bit like a mind over matter cliche.

55
00:03:56,969 --> 00:04:02,674
If my car breaks down and I lose a day's pay, that is hard.

56
00:04:02,955 --> 00:04:09,155
It's not just a gap in expectations, it's an objective mess.

57
00:04:09,995 --> 00:04:13,534
I look at those influencers with their clean desks

58
00:04:13,534 --> 00:04:21,780
and organised lives, and I feel like I'm the only one whose life is a jagged mountain range.

59
00:04:21,980 --> 00:04:23,700
But that's the trick.

60
00:04:23,900 --> 00:04:28,980
You are comparing your behind the scenes footage to their highlight reel.

61
00:04:29,724 --> 00:04:39,125
A private life is a happy life means realizing that the smooth lives you see online are carefully edited performances.

62
00:04:39,645 --> 00:04:45,445
Nobody posts a video of themselves crying over a spilled latte or a frayed wire.

63
00:04:46,230 --> 00:04:52,910
By comparing your messy reality to a digital lie, you're paying an unhappiness tax.

64
00:04:53,190 --> 00:04:55,390
You're not just solving the problem.

65
00:04:55,349 --> 00:04:58,350
You're wasting energy asking, why me?

66
00:04:59,025 --> 00:05:01,945
The unhappiness tax.

67
00:05:02,625 --> 00:05:06,825
I am definitely overpaying on that one.

68
00:05:07,344 --> 00:05:17,150
I guess I've let the Internet set my baseline for what normal looks like, and normal doesn't include struggle.

69
00:05:17,989 --> 00:05:25,710
But it still doesn't explain why I feel so much more overwhelmed than my parents ever did.

70
00:05:26,745 --> 00:05:32,225
They didn't have high speed Internet, but they seemed steadier.

71
00:05:32,344 --> 00:05:36,065
That's because they weren't paying the complexity tax.

72
00:05:36,424 --> 00:05:44,830
Let's talk about why our easy modern life is actually making our brains feel much heavier than theirs ever did.

73
00:05:45,030 --> 00:05:46,270
I'm ready.

74
00:05:46,710 --> 00:05:55,070
I need to understand why having everything at my fingertips is making my life feel so difficult.

75
00:05:55,645 --> 00:05:59,605
Daniel, I think you hit on something very profound there.

76
00:05:59,885 --> 00:06:03,205
You mentioned your parents, and it's true.

77
00:06:03,245 --> 00:06:11,365
They didn't have to manage a digital identity, five messaging apps, and a 20 four seven global news cycle.

78
00:06:12,260 --> 00:06:13,740
They just lived.

79
00:06:14,340 --> 00:06:19,580
What we are experiencing now is what I call the complexity tax.

80
00:06:20,020 --> 00:06:24,700
We have traded physical hardship for psychological complexity.

81
00:06:25,594 --> 00:06:30,755
In the past, hard meant manual labor or physical survival.

82
00:06:31,354 --> 00:06:38,275
Today, hard is the sheer volume of choices we have to make every hour.

83
00:06:39,140 --> 00:06:46,140
Research shows that every decision, no matter how small, drains a bit of your mental energy.

84
00:06:46,580 --> 00:06:53,660
By 10AM, you've probably made more micro decisions than your grandfather made in a week.

85
00:06:54,275 --> 00:06:58,875
I hear the decision fatigue argument, Emma, but I have to push back.

86
00:06:59,155 --> 00:07:05,035
If complexity is the price of freedom, are you saying we should actually want less freedom?

87
00:07:05,395 --> 00:07:09,595
I can learn any language, work from anywhere, and buy anything.

88
00:07:10,260 --> 00:07:12,700
My grandfather didn't have those choices,

89
00:07:12,739 --> 00:07:14,759
but I doubt he was happier

90
00:07:14,759 --> 00:07:18,060
because he was stuck in one town with one job.

91
00:07:18,499 --> 00:07:23,019
I'd rather be frazzled with options than bored with none.

92
00:07:24,034 --> 00:07:28,315
Isn't this complexity tax just a luxury problem?

93
00:07:28,674 --> 00:07:33,674
We are essentially complaining that our lives are too full of opportunity.

94
00:07:33,955 --> 00:07:37,435
It's not just about too many options, Daniel.

95
00:07:37,779 --> 00:07:40,700
It's about the erosion of the self.

96
00:07:41,140 --> 00:07:44,140
This tax isn't just a fee we pay.

97
00:07:44,260 --> 00:07:46,620
It's a threat to our identity.

98
00:07:47,059 --> 00:07:56,115
Because we are constantly optimizing and managing our digital personas, we've lost the ability to simply exist in silence.

99
00:07:56,234 --> 00:08:03,155
In 2026, if you aren't being productive or connected, you feel like you're disappearing.

100
00:08:03,755 --> 00:08:07,555
We've traded our inner peace for a performance identity.

101
00:08:08,049 --> 00:08:09,850
You aren't just Daniel.

102
00:08:09,810 --> 00:08:14,410
You're a brand, a worker, and a user all at once.

103
00:08:15,010 --> 00:08:17,290
That is the real cost.

104
00:08:17,650 --> 00:08:19,530
That's a dark way to put it.

105
00:08:20,145 --> 00:08:25,705
You're saying that the complexity tax is actually stealing our personality?

106
00:08:26,465 --> 00:08:28,025
I can feel that.

107
00:08:28,624 --> 00:08:34,184
When I'm waiting for a bus, I can't just stand there for two minutes without pulling out my phone.

108
00:08:34,880 --> 00:08:37,800
I've lost the ability to be bored,

109
00:08:37,919 --> 00:08:43,480
and because of that, I feel like I've lost the space to think my own thoughts.

110
00:08:44,240 --> 00:08:47,400
I'm just a processor for everyone else's information.

111
00:08:48,265 --> 00:08:51,165
If I'm always optimising my English

112
00:08:51,165 --> 00:08:57,345
or my career, I never actually get to meet the person I am when the work stops.

113
00:08:58,105 --> 00:09:00,785
That's not just a frazzled brain.

114
00:09:01,225 --> 00:09:02,705
That's a hollow life.

115
00:09:03,310 --> 00:09:04,470
Exactly.

116
00:09:04,990 --> 00:09:09,990
The tax is that your identity becomes tied to your performance.

117
00:09:10,430 --> 00:09:14,770
A private life is a happy life is a survival strategy

118
00:09:14,770 --> 00:09:18,035
because it allows you to reclaim the parts of yourself

119
00:09:18,035 --> 00:09:20,615
that aren't for sale or for show.

120
00:09:20,895 --> 00:09:25,895
If you don't pay attention, the complexity will replace your character.

121
00:09:26,415 --> 00:09:32,855
We have the freedom to do everything, yet we feel like we have no freedom to do nothing.

122
00:09:33,659 --> 00:09:36,020
The freedom to do nothing.

123
00:09:36,780 --> 00:09:39,220
I haven't had that in a long time.

124
00:09:40,060 --> 00:09:45,140
I guess I've been so busy juggling the flaming chainsaws of the modern world

125
00:09:45,179 --> 00:09:49,945
that I haven't noticed I'm not even the one who chose to juggle them.

126
00:09:50,465 --> 00:09:54,185
I just picked them up because everyone else was doing it.

127
00:09:54,785 --> 00:09:58,744
But even if I want to simplify, I feel like I can't.

128
00:09:59,590 --> 00:10:03,390
If I drop the chainsaws, I'll be left with nothing.

129
00:10:03,829 --> 00:10:09,150
And that fear is exactly why the resistance to life is so high.

130
00:10:09,429 --> 00:10:11,629
We aren't just fighting our schedules.

131
00:10:11,875 --> 00:10:16,235
We are fighting the fear of what happens if we slow down.

132
00:10:16,755 --> 00:10:17,735
Okay, Emma.

133
00:10:17,735 --> 00:10:20,715
Let's talk about this resistance thing.

134
00:10:20,675 --> 00:10:23,495
You're basically saying that if I just accepted

135
00:10:23,495 --> 00:10:25,895
that my laptop charger was broken

136
00:10:25,895 --> 00:10:29,970
and my neighbors were loud, I wouldn't feel so miserable.

137
00:10:30,489 --> 00:10:33,970
But that feels like a very passive way to live.

138
00:10:34,010 --> 00:10:39,730
If I just say it is what it is to everything, I'm just a doormat for the universe.

139
00:10:40,275 --> 00:10:43,735
I'm angry because things should be better.

140
00:10:43,735 --> 00:10:47,515
I'm resisting because I have standards.

141
00:10:47,875 --> 00:10:52,475
If I stop fighting the hardness, aren't I just giving up?

142
00:10:53,050 --> 00:10:57,490
There is a huge difference between acceptance and giving up, Daniel.

143
00:10:57,850 --> 00:11:00,130
Giving up means you stop trying.

144
00:11:00,730 --> 00:11:05,730
Acceptance means you stop fighting the reality of what has already happened.

145
00:11:06,615 --> 00:11:09,215
There's a famous equation in psychology.

146
00:11:09,574 --> 00:11:13,215
Suffering equals pain times resistance.

147
00:11:13,814 --> 00:11:16,495
The pain is the broken charger.

148
00:11:16,454 --> 00:11:17,935
That's a fixed fact.

149
00:11:18,790 --> 00:11:22,670
The suffering is the ten minutes you spent yelling at the wall,

150
00:11:22,790 --> 00:11:25,790
the hour you spent worrying about the cost,

151
00:11:25,750 --> 00:11:28,510
and the bad mood you carried into your lunch.

152
00:11:28,709 --> 00:11:33,629
You can't always control the pain, but you can control the resistance.

153
00:11:34,215 --> 00:11:38,095
So you're saying I'm multiplying my own problems.

154
00:11:38,215 --> 00:11:45,455
I have one problem, the charger, and I turn it into 10 problems by being upset about it.

155
00:11:45,815 --> 00:11:49,535
I can see the logic, but it's incredibly difficult to practice.

156
00:11:50,170 --> 00:11:54,930
When I'm in the middle of a mess, my brain doesn't want to accept.

157
00:11:55,209 --> 00:11:57,250
It wants to argue.

158
00:11:57,290 --> 00:11:59,810
It wants to find someone to blame.

159
00:12:00,170 --> 00:12:03,570
I feel like my anger is a form of protection.

160
00:12:04,275 --> 00:12:13,434
If I'm not angry about things going wrong, then I'm just okay with life being difficult, and that feels dangerous.

161
00:12:13,794 --> 00:12:17,355
It feels dangerous because your ego wants to be in control.

162
00:12:18,029 --> 00:12:20,790
But your anger doesn't fix the charger.

163
00:12:20,750 --> 00:12:22,629
It only drains your battery.

164
00:12:23,229 --> 00:12:26,710
Spend effort only on what's truly worth it.

165
00:12:27,229 --> 00:12:33,109
Is it worth spending two hours of your limited mental energy being mad at a piece of plastic?

166
00:12:33,645 --> 00:12:38,485
When you resist reality, you are essentially arguing with the past.

167
00:12:38,765 --> 00:12:40,885
It's the ultimate waste of time.

168
00:12:41,405 --> 00:12:50,030
A private life is a happy life also means having a private peace that isn't easily disturbed by external inconveniences.

169
00:12:50,709 --> 00:12:59,869
I'm starting to realize that I spend about 50% of my day just being annoyed that things aren't perfect.

170
00:13:00,635 --> 00:13:02,515
I'm fighting the traffic.

171
00:13:02,475 --> 00:13:04,915
I'm fighting the slow Internet.

172
00:13:04,954 --> 00:13:06,995
I'm even fighting the weather.

173
00:13:07,275 --> 00:13:13,955
It's like I'm in a boxing match with the entire world, and the world isn't even hitting back.

174
00:13:14,140 --> 00:13:17,540
I'm just punching the air and getting tired.

175
00:13:18,219 --> 00:13:24,420
I guess if I just allowed things to be hard without adding my own drama to them,

176
00:13:24,459 --> 00:13:28,900
I'd have a lot more energy left over to actually fix the problems.

177
00:13:29,245 --> 00:13:30,405
Exactly.

178
00:13:30,845 --> 00:13:34,005
When you stop resisting, you gain clarity.

179
00:13:34,445 --> 00:13:40,725
You move from why is this happening to me to what is the next logical step.

180
00:13:41,530 --> 00:13:44,450
Acceptance isn't about liking the situation.

181
00:13:44,650 --> 00:13:48,290
It's about acknowledging it so you can deal with it effectively.

182
00:13:48,890 --> 00:13:51,890
You're no longer a victim of the hardness.

183
00:13:52,010 --> 00:13:53,650
You're a manager of it.

184
00:13:53,850 --> 00:13:57,010
It sounds like a much quieter way to live.

185
00:13:57,655 --> 00:14:01,535
But, Emma, doesn't this lead to a very boring life?

186
00:14:01,895 --> 00:14:09,775
If we just accept everything and de escalate our emotions, do we lose the drive to improve?

187
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:15,600
It feels like hard is a bad thing we should always avoid.

188
00:14:16,040 --> 00:14:20,000
But isn't there some value in the struggle itself?

189
00:14:20,199 --> 00:14:22,400
That is the growth paradox.

190
00:14:23,204 --> 00:14:28,525
We hate the hardness while we are in it, but we wouldn't be who we are without it.

191
00:14:29,045 --> 00:14:34,365
Let's look at why easy might actually be the most dangerous thing for your future.

192
00:14:34,565 --> 00:14:35,885
I'm curious.

193
00:14:36,084 --> 00:14:41,140
Tell me why I should be grateful for this wet cement brain of mine.

194
00:14:41,100 --> 00:14:47,620
Daniel, I want to challenge your idea that hard is a bad thing we should always avoid.

195
00:14:47,980 --> 00:14:49,620
Think about your muscles.

196
00:14:49,900 --> 00:14:56,145
If you go to the gym and lift weights that are easy, your muscles have no reason to change.

197
00:14:56,345 --> 00:15:02,625
They only grow when they meet resistance, when the weight is actually difficult to move.

198
00:15:03,385 --> 00:15:04,785
Life is the same way.

199
00:15:05,630 --> 00:15:08,629
We hate the hardness while we are in it,

200
00:15:08,670 --> 00:15:15,190
but the growth paradox is that hard is the only environment where meaningful change happens.

201
00:15:15,549 --> 00:15:21,955
If everything were frictionless, you would be exactly the same person you were ten years ago.

202
00:15:22,075 --> 00:15:25,555
I knew you were going to bring up the gym, Emma.

203
00:15:25,915 --> 00:15:29,875
It's the classic no pain, no gain argument.

204
00:15:30,299 --> 00:15:35,200
But there's a big difference between choosing to lift a heavy weight for thirty minutes

205
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:40,420
and being forced to deal with a heavy life for months on end.

206
00:15:40,859 --> 00:15:43,780
In the gym, I can put the weights down.

207
00:15:44,605 --> 00:15:47,125
In life, I can't.

208
00:15:47,805 --> 00:15:54,245
I don't feel like I'm growing when I'm stressed about my bills or my broken laptop.

209
00:15:54,605 --> 00:15:56,165
I just feel tired.

210
00:15:57,180 --> 00:16:02,580
Are you saying I should be thankful for the stress because it's building character?

211
00:16:03,020 --> 00:16:09,060
Because right now, I'd trade all that character for a week of peace and quiet.

212
00:16:09,595 --> 00:16:15,315
I'm not saying you should enjoy the suffering, but you should respect the process.

213
00:16:16,074 --> 00:16:22,595
Spend effort only on what's truly worth it, and building resilience is worth everything.

214
00:16:23,560 --> 00:16:29,999
When you navigate a difficult week without breaking, you are expanding your capacity.

215
00:16:30,520 --> 00:16:34,800
The next time a laptop breaks, it won't feel like a mountain.

216
00:16:35,185 --> 00:16:39,865
It'll feel like a molehill because you've already handled worse.

217
00:16:40,545 --> 00:16:46,825
A private life is a happy life, means your internal strength isn't something you show off.

218
00:16:47,449 --> 00:16:55,010
It's the quiet confidence that comes from knowing you've survived hard before, and you can do it again.

219
00:16:55,449 --> 00:17:01,410
So life is just a series of increasingly difficult levels like a video game.

220
00:17:02,025 --> 00:17:05,425
That doesn't sound very cosy, Emma.

221
00:17:05,785 --> 00:17:07,824
It sounds exhausting.

222
00:17:08,745 --> 00:17:15,639
If the reward for handling hard is just more hard, what's the point?

223
00:17:16,319 --> 00:17:21,879
I feel like I'm waiting for a finish line where life finally becomes easy,

224
00:17:22,160 --> 00:17:25,560
but you're telling me that the finish line doesn't exist.

225
00:17:26,465 --> 00:17:33,464
You're saying that the goal is just to become a person who can carry heavier and heavier things.

226
00:17:34,385 --> 00:17:36,904
Is that really all there is?

227
00:17:37,345 --> 00:17:40,105
The point isn't just to carry more weight.

228
00:17:40,520 --> 00:17:45,519
It's that the things that used to be heavy eventually feel light.

229
00:17:46,040 --> 00:17:48,480
That is the true reward.

230
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:54,000
The easy life you're looking for isn't a place where problems don't exist.

231
00:17:54,564 --> 00:18:00,604
It's a state where you are so capable that those problems don't overwhelm you anymore.

232
00:18:01,125 --> 00:18:03,804
You don't want a life without mountains.

233
00:18:04,084 --> 00:18:06,445
You want to be a better climber.

234
00:18:07,140 --> 00:18:11,739
The hardness is the training ground for the person you want to become.

235
00:18:12,100 --> 00:18:14,219
A better climber.

236
00:18:15,300 --> 00:18:20,939
I suppose that's a better way to look at it than just being a victim of the terrain.

237
00:18:21,885 --> 00:18:26,964
I'm still not thankful for my wet cement brain today,

238
00:18:27,165 --> 00:18:32,324
but I can see how pushing through this session is a form of training.

239
00:18:33,320 --> 00:18:37,919
It's about not letting the difficulty dictate my direction.

240
00:18:37,960 --> 00:18:39,199
Exactly.

241
00:18:39,640 --> 00:18:45,520
You are practicing the most important skill of all practical endurance.

242
00:18:46,455 --> 00:18:52,254
It's not about why life is hard, but about how you choose to walk through it.

243
00:18:52,935 --> 00:18:54,075
Okay, Emma.

244
00:18:54,075 --> 00:19:01,534
I'm trying to internalize this idea of being a better climber, but I'm ready for the actual tools.

245
00:19:02,190 --> 00:19:05,429
If I'm in the middle of a week where everything is breaking,

246
00:19:05,390 --> 00:19:09,990
my energy is low, and the complexity tax is draining me,

247
00:19:10,110 --> 00:19:12,629
how do I actually endure it?

248
00:19:12,990 --> 00:19:15,030
I don't want a lecture on mindset.

249
00:19:15,285 --> 00:19:20,445
I want to know what to do when I wake up and that wet cement feeling is back.

250
00:19:20,805 --> 00:19:25,084
How do I stop the hardness from paralyzing me?

251
00:19:25,525 --> 00:19:31,719
The most effective tool for practical endurance is the next hour rule.

252
00:19:32,319 --> 00:19:35,380
When life is hard, we usually get overwhelmed

253
00:19:35,380 --> 00:19:36,980
because we are thinking about the

254
00:19:36,980 --> 00:19:40,759
next month, the next year, or the entire mountain.

255
00:19:41,775 --> 00:19:47,494
Practical endurance means you shrink your world until it is small enough to manage.

256
00:19:47,935 --> 00:19:50,614
You don't think about the project deadline.

257
00:19:50,655 --> 00:19:53,254
You think about the next sixty minutes.

258
00:19:54,170 --> 00:20:01,490
What is the one thing you can do in the next hour to make the situation 1% better?

259
00:20:02,170 --> 00:20:05,810
Spend effort only on what's truly worth it.

260
00:20:05,850 --> 00:20:11,534
And in a crisis, the only thing worth your effort is the very next step.

261
00:20:12,375 --> 00:20:14,175
Shrinking the world.

262
00:20:14,615 --> 00:20:16,574
I can see how that helps.

263
00:20:16,775 --> 00:20:20,334
It's like putting on blinders so you don't see the storm.

264
00:20:20,500 --> 00:20:23,740
You just see the path right in front of your feet.

265
00:20:24,420 --> 00:20:28,459
But what about when I'm just physically and mentally exhausted?

266
00:20:28,980 --> 00:20:32,860
Sometimes the next step is just to go back to sleep.

267
00:20:33,615 --> 00:20:36,694
I feel guilty when I can't keep up the pace.

268
00:20:37,054 --> 00:20:43,894
If I'm scaling down my life just to survive the week, am I losing my momentum?

269
00:20:44,414 --> 00:20:45,334
Not at all.

270
00:20:45,909 --> 00:20:50,109
But I'm going to give you a rule that might feel uncomfortable.

271
00:20:50,630 --> 00:20:54,909
If it's hard, do it badly, but do it.

272
00:20:55,350 --> 00:21:02,004
We often stop because we think if we can't do a task perfectly, it's not worth doing.

273
00:21:02,365 --> 00:21:04,004
That's a lie.

274
00:21:04,285 --> 00:21:09,685
If you're too tired to study for an hour, read one sentence badly.

275
00:21:09,965 --> 00:21:15,044
If you're too overwhelmed to clean the house, wash one spoon badly.

276
00:21:15,780 --> 00:21:22,139
Acceptance of bad progress is the only way to maintain momentum during a storm.

277
00:21:22,420 --> 00:21:24,619
And here is the second rule.

278
00:21:25,220 --> 00:21:27,740
No complaining before noon.

279
00:21:28,365 --> 00:21:30,804
No complaining before noon?

280
00:21:30,924 --> 00:21:33,924
That's going to be the hardest part of the whole script.

281
00:21:34,365 --> 00:21:36,484
Why that specific rule?

282
00:21:36,765 --> 00:21:39,764
Because complaining is a form of resistance.

283
00:21:40,640 --> 00:21:48,040
Every time you say, This is so hard, you are reinforcing the hardness in your brain.

284
00:21:48,320 --> 00:21:51,239
You are feeding the complexity tax.

285
00:21:51,600 --> 00:21:53,860
By staying silent about the struggle

286
00:21:53,860 --> 00:21:57,625
until noon, you force your brain to focus on the

287
00:21:57,625 --> 00:22:01,004
next hour rule instead of the drama.

288
00:22:01,444 --> 00:22:08,044
You have to understand, Daniel, if you don't shrink your world, the world will crush you.

289
00:22:08,799 --> 00:22:15,879
The complexity of 2026 is too big for a human brain to carry all at once.

290
00:22:16,400 --> 00:22:21,480
If you don't learn to put on those blinders, you will simply burn out.

291
00:22:22,275 --> 00:22:27,114
If you don't shrink your world, the world will crush you.

292
00:22:27,875 --> 00:22:32,715
That's a heavy warning, but I think it's the truth I needed to hear.

293
00:22:33,395 --> 00:22:40,080
I've been trying to carry the whole globe on my back, and I'm surprised that my knees are shaking.

294
00:22:40,680 --> 00:22:46,639
I'm going to try the next hour rule and the no complaining challenge today.

295
00:22:47,160 --> 00:22:49,600
I'm not going to worry about the whole week.

296
00:22:49,975 --> 00:22:53,455
I'm just going to focus on finishing this conversation.

297
00:22:53,895 --> 00:22:55,614
And that's a win.

298
00:22:55,655 --> 00:22:57,695
You're doing it right now.

299
00:22:57,815 --> 00:23:01,294
You showed up, you engaged, and you're learning.

300
00:23:01,655 --> 00:23:04,334
That is the definition of endurance.

301
00:23:05,220 --> 00:23:06,540
Thanks, Emma.

302
00:23:06,660 --> 00:23:09,100
I feel a little bit lighter already.

303
00:23:09,780 --> 00:23:16,300
And to all of you listening, we know some of you are in that wet cement phase right now too.

304
00:23:16,834 --> 00:23:19,675
We want to hear how you're handling it.

305
00:23:19,954 --> 00:23:20,954
Exactly.

306
00:23:21,235 --> 00:23:24,074
Here is your cozy English challenge.

307
00:23:24,595 --> 00:23:27,114
Apply the next hour rule.

308
00:23:27,314 --> 00:23:35,070
Pick one thing, just one, and do it in the next sixty minutes, even if you do it badly.

309
00:23:35,590 --> 00:23:40,269
And try the no complaining before noon rule tomorrow morning.

310
00:23:40,709 --> 00:23:43,230
Leave a comment below and answer this.

311
00:23:44,034 --> 00:23:50,554
What is the one next hour step you're taking to shrink your world today?

312
00:23:51,314 --> 00:23:55,915
Your stories of endurance are what keep this community so strong.

313
00:23:56,540 --> 00:23:58,340
They truly are.

314
00:23:58,620 --> 00:24:06,179
Thank you for subscribing, for sharing your journey with us, and for being part of the Cozy English.

315
00:24:06,620 --> 00:24:13,164
Don't forget to download the full PDF script in the description to review all the resistance

316
00:24:13,164 --> 00:24:16,304
and endurance vocabulary we covered today.

317
00:24:16,745 --> 00:24:19,584
Take it one hour at a time, everyone.

318
00:24:19,704 --> 00:24:21,904
I'll see you in the next episode.

319
00:24:22,105 --> 00:24:23,024
Goodbye.

320
00:24:23,304 --> 00:24:25,645
Goodbye, and stay cozy.
